As part of this year‚Äôs activities marking Black History Month at BBL, parents and their children (seventy-five altogether) with five staff, visited the National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, DC, on Wednesday, February 26, 2020. The one-day trip, organized by our Guidance Department, was in recognition of parents (from both campuses) who attended the Fall Guidance Saturday Workshop back in November. Parents are advised to stay tuned for details about future Guidance Department programs and the benefits that come with participating.

post_text:
"Frederick Douglass" by Robert Hayden

When it is finally ours, this freedom, this liberty, this beautiful
and terrible thing, needful to man as air,
usable as earth; when it belongs at last to all,
when it is truly instinct, brain matter, diastole, systole,
reflex action; when it is finally won; when it is more
than the gaudy mumbo jumbo of politicians:
this man, this Douglass, this former slave, this Negro
beaten to his knees, exiled, visioning a world
where none is lonely, none hunted, alien,
this man, superb in love and logic, this man
shall be remembered. Oh, not with statues‚Äô rhetoric,
not with legends and poems and wreaths of bronze alone,
but with the lives grown out of his life, the lives
fleshing his dream of the beautiful, needful thing.

post_text:
"BLK History Month" by Nikki Giovanni

If Black History Month is not
viable then wind does not
carry the seeds and drop them
on fertile ground
rain does not
dampen the land
and encourage the seeds
to root
sun does not
warm the earth
and kiss the seedlings
and tell them plain:
You‚Äôre As Good As Anybody Else
You‚Äôve Got A Place Here, Too

post_text: Our 5th Grade SOAR Team had the opportunity to visit Cold Spring Harbor‚Äôs DNA Learning Center! Our SOAR students became scientists, jumping into the world of cells, cell- structure, chromosomes, and DNA. We had the opportunity to extract DNA from wheat by dissolving lipids from within the cell. We also researched genetic mutations and observed how these mutations have led to various transformations in fruit flies. Last, but not least, we visited their museum, which was dedicated to the theory of evolution. The Museum allowed us to venture back almost 5 million years to see the transformation of the human skeleton, as well as view a replica of the very famous 5000-year-old Otzi, the mummified corpse of an iceman who lived in the Otzal Alps on the Italian-Austrian border during the Stone Age.
